from my latest w/ @misskaylajj: 
jane doe, as she is known in the case files, knew of her teacher josh frenchâ€™s creepy reputation.

it was an open secret that he hand-picked the best looking girls to sit at the front of his 8th grade social studies class at mission middle school in escondido union school district. from his viewpoint at the lectern, he could look directly down their shirts and many said he did so quite openly. 
more than one student reported frenchâ€™s behavior to more than one teacher. at least one dozen middle school girls told at least three school workers what was happening.

one teacher suggested they â€œwrite incident reports.â€ another said â€œnot to wear low cut shirts.â€ â€œput binders in front of [your] chests when [youâ€™re] near frenchâ€ to block his gaze, said another, according to investigative reports that emerged later.

as each girl came forward with a new story, it appears teachers kept coming up with new ways for the girls to adjust their own behavior or appearance. meanwhile, frenchâ€™s colleagues made way for him â€“ a young white man who brought energy and authoritative presence to a primarily latino, high-poverty middle school â€“ to be himself.

the missed warning signs in this story are shocking. and no one acted on any of them, until jane doe reported that french raped her in a locked classroom. link in bio. 
repost of @voiceofsandiego illustration by @wonderfall. this story is part of a massive investigation into sexual misconduct in schools started by ashly mcglone.

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

.

.
.
stay tuned.
.
.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

before yâ€™all start questioning me, hereâ€™s my take on abortion:
i am pro-choice (i know, shocking). i believe that as people, and because we live in america (â€œthe land of the freeâ€), we have the right to make our own choices. if a woman feels as if she needs an abortion, no one should stop her. however, i believe that an abortion should be the absolute last thing that someone needs to resort to. if adoption, foster care, or any other solution is not an option, then yes, an abortion should be available. the two things that upset me the most about the â€œpro-life movementâ€ are 1) when a woman has this child, will you, the pro-life supporter, help to make sure this child has a safe home? will you make sure that this child doesnâ€™t grow up abused? will you make sure that this child never has to worry about their next meal? will you make sure that this child is wanted, loved, and cared for in the home that theyâ€™re in? 2) getting rid of abortions is just about the worst thing you could do for the movement. without safe abortions, self-inflicted abortions & dangerous other â€œsolutionsâ€ will become even more common. they could be potentially harming themselves. instead of preaching about getting rid of abortions, how about you go talk to & help these mothers who will make a choice that is sometimes life devastating. -

text:
on monday morning, senator kamala harris announced that sheâ€™s running for president. this was no surpriseâ€”harrisâ€™s run has been rumored for months.

as the daughter of immigrants, with a record of upholding rights for marginalized communities on several occasions, harris should be an ideal progressive candidate. many sex workers and sex worker rights advocates, however, vehemently disagree.

last year, harris, the former attorney general of california, helped champion the allow states and victims to fight online sex trafficking act (fosta), a piece of legislation sex workers and advocacy groups warned would have a disastrous impact on sex workersâ€™ livesâ€”and they were right. fosta passed in april 2018 with harrisâ€™s support, and she released a statement touting how proud she was to have helped move this bill through congress, saying she has â€œwitnessed firsthand the difficulty of charging sex trafficking sitesâ€”even for crimes as egregious as pimping minors.â€ harris and other fosta supporters claimed its passage would allow authorities to shut down websites like backpage.comâ€”an escort advertising site that was an alleged hotbed for trafficking activity. it was also a primary source of income for many independent sex workers. backpage and other advertising sites allowed sex workers to be financially independent and find and screen work for themselves, off the streets and away from actual traffickers or abusive â€œmanagersâ€ and pimps.

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
cum one, cum all!
welcome to my art page & brace yourselves for a spiel on the #femininedivine ! although it's true that a picture is worth a thousand words, i wanted to express a complex idea using some of my own:

first and foremost, i want to make clear that a woman's power does not come from her sexuality.

true #feminism embraces the inherent differences in men and women through their physical, behavioral, emotional and psychological beings. it is imperative we affirm and celebrate differences in #masculine and #feminine qualities as wonderful and complementary. as individuals and a community, we must acknowledge how each are made stronger by the presence of the other, rather than let so be misconstrued as evidence for either being superior. educating ourselves is just as important as raising our children to understand and appreciate the #equality between sexes.

#autonomy is #empowerment in and of itself! it is dangerous to imply that a woman's worth is indicative by how they allow or deny their bodies to be touched as a demonstration of power, and even more so to synonymize that with responses to the solicitation of men's desires. not only does this objectify women and reduce their value to looks vs personality, but also encourages gender stereotypes that feed #heteronormative dating scripts, promotes sexual manipulation that turns the bedroom into a battleground for unrelated conflicts which can exacerbate the toxicity of rape culture and, ironically enough, repress women's sexuality.
don't get me wrong: it is always acceptable to deny sex, but never in an attempt to alter a partner's behavior/emotions. this applies to both women and men.

whether itâ€™s sex, food, or life experiences, societyâ€™s view of the ideal woman as undemanding and self-restrained pressures women to repeatedly say â€œno.â€
but what if we taught ourselves that power can lie in asserting desires, even if it means saying "yes?" #power can be knowing that our bodies are not rewards for good behavior but living, breathing entities housing human beings & knowing that decisions based on your body are your own, and yours alone

flower shower (2016)
colored pencils, 8.5" x 11"

#endrant

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer".
.
in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytic until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer".

in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytic until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
#theoscars

since i am returning to instagram right as the #oscarnoms are announced, i wanted to give a few thoughts. for a long time weâ€™ve know that the oscars are mostly a political shamble.. you have the â€œworlds most moral peopleâ€ (yet most corrupt? #metoo) making bold political statements and poking fun at everyone who might have an even remotely different view than them while at the same time are under constant ridicule for every â€œmisstepâ€ the have that you forget that the whole point of the show is to honor artist for their extraordinary work in film. 
this year is the shining example of the downward trajectory that weâ€™ve been seeing over the years. for example, i can think of 3 or 4 different films that should have the spot that black panther is currently taking (the biggest sub being a star is born). but because black panther is more politically relevant and (as a result) did well at the box office, it gets to take away the chance of a better made film from winning that award! donâ€™t get me wrong, i really enjoyed black panther... i thought it was a nice refreshing film in the mcu with the best villain yet.. but there were tons of problems with that movie should disqualify it from being nominated.. hell, the dark knight didnâ€™t get nominated and that was a masterpiece! now, because the oscars are so political, letâ€™s just yield and say â€œthey have to have a film like this nominatedâ€ .. fine whatever.. but a film that can convey a similar message, and even more relevant messages than the ones told in black panther, is found in very good film that came out called sorry to bother you... this film is one that not many people saw but conveyed very political messages in very creative and original ways.. and it gets nothing... in my opinion, the academy has lost it.... and i couldnâ€™t have been more disappointed with the nominations this year and, frankly, iâ€™m fed up with it... so, until i see something encouraging with the oscars, iâ€™m done with them and wonâ€™t further cover anything from them..
thank you for entertaining my meaningless opinion!

text:
celebrating me across the years!
.
itâ€™s been a journey! a 3 year old baby starting a new journey in a new household, unsure of herself and feeling different.
.
i grew up very much loved but i never quite fit in! bullied, teased, lost and trying to find my path.
.
middle school was rough! the pink photo is when a bully took my year book and wrote â€œbitchâ€ across my photo in pink highlighter. i colored it in to try and hide the word. even through being teased i found my voice in talent shows.
.
accepted into the school of the arts in high school and i finally felt good in my own skin! then i became a mom at 16. i lost my way.
.
over the years i have struggled, cried, screamed, hid from the world and lost my voice.
.
at 48 i found my path and one step at a time iâ€™m coming out of my cocoon. wonder what colors my wings will be!

i always say, that the most painful state a wo (man) could find his/herself in, is when s(he) has the best job, the best spouse, the most beautiful house and yet is so very much unfulfilled in life.

there is is sense of fulfilment that will never come from what or who you have. this is a sense of fulfilment you'll have only when you know without doubt you're actually doing what god has specifically called you to do.
you have a purpose. you not just on earth to fade away.

text: yours truly on "charlie rose" - punctuation marks indicative of the show vs the man himself, in the mid 1990s. (toward the mention of #metoo, we wish to differentiate between the kind of sexual harassment mr. rose tossed our way and the truly unfair, horrific variety to which he reportedly subjected women in his employ. pathetically enough, in our case, it was the year 1988 and we were astonished enough that a man in his position played a very aggressive version of footsies during a damn interview. afterwards, we said as much to the segment producer, a woman about our age, who brushed it off by saying, "oh, that's charlie. he's got tons of sexual harassment suits going on.") anyway, back to the semi prettiness of the way we were, we do wish to say that mr. rose was one of our favorite people who ever interviewed us. he not only asked intelligent questions, but he seemed to find us clever enough never to condescend. if you read our previous post, you may notice a small theme. david letterman was another definite favorite, and we're sure he'll understand that our #1 spot goes to tom snyder. we absolutely adored him and it bloody might've been mutual. we have quite a few things to say about hollywood - such as a b level career might address. (and please don't rush to say it was "a": we know as and respect the expanse, and dizzying heights of their careers and, on occasion, the person themselves, far and away a separate thing from stardom. thanking our friends who don't care to be identified by name, bless you both, for sending this link. y'all were right - we did need a good memory today. it's been a mutha of a week. and here is much love for the many kindnesses through these long years.ğŸ’“ğŸ™‹ğŸƒğŸŒ’ğŸ•°ï¸

.
i often get asked why i invest so much of my time helping people i donâ€™t know. the answer is simple. this world is in desperate need of healing. there are battles being fought every day that you and i know absolutely nothing about. there are people suffering in silence when they shouldnâ€™t be. their voices deserve to be heard. and their stories deserve to be told.
.
if i had what iâ€™ve always been for others, a lot of the things i experienced in my own life could have been alleviated or avoided. no one deserves to go through life feeling unloved and alone. instead of telling someone that things will be okay, give them an opportunity to tell you what actually happened to them. give them permission to speak freely so they can confront their fears and find solutions to their problems.
.
serving others is a noble thing to doâ€”and thereâ€™s no shame in accepting help or guidance when itâ€™s offered to you. just be sure itâ€™s coming from a source whose heart is pure and intentions are true.

text:
i get a lot of things from my momâ€”a slightly off-kilter sense of humor, the thrill of a high-end bargain and an alarming love for baked goods. iâ€™m not there yet, but i hope to inherit her sense of place, her strength and her faith. i keep thinking iâ€™m too old to look to her for emotional support, but honestly, iâ€™ll  accept it selfishly. abuse can break a family, but she has been a fierce ally and i appreciate her more everyday. what has happened nearly broke her in half and at times i struggle with being the cause of secondary trauma to her. i need to remind myself that this shameful load was transferred to me by a man who made it a career to hurt others. when the shame is so heavy that i feel my knees buckle, i look to her strength and keep going..
. .
.
.
.
.

text:
died a grocer

asked to explain the meaning of an epitaph he had written for his tombstone -"born, a human being; died, a wholesale grocer"-the businessman replied, "i was so busy selling groceries, i did not have to get married and have a family. i was successful. but i was so busy making a living, i never had time to live." many of today have a similar problem.

life is just a vapor, full of hustle and bustle that spend all our time doing "important things" in pursuit for money (owoyi sha ni).
we must consider our actions, in terms of our few short so let us not be so busy making a living that we forget to make a life.  #goodmorning

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
aviation: the wright brothers (2/10) by nicholas jones, 03 january 2019. -

whenever i wright - i feel like iâ€™m creating something,
something human - like a cohesive unit of literary organs,
pumping the blood symbolically from the beginning to the end,
then back to the beginning - to create new life all over again,

the process is a pleasure plus tenfold,
taking the air and the colors of the wind,
to define the time that iâ€™m living in - 
because icons only become iconic,
whenever people start to pay attention,

dreams only take flight when it all feels wright,
when the sunlight shining bright canâ€™t dim your shine,
so learn to fly and master it - because then and only then,
will the icon be as iconic as he was when he first took flight,

he might have failed a million times - and so will i,
before i can finally learn to fly - and wonâ€™t it just feel great,
to finally master the poetic form - in all of its forms,
through the lens of a thunderstorm - and the art of aviation. -

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text: what does word â€œboundariesâ€ mean to you? i think itâ€™s something that on many occasions is not spoken about enough until the situation becomes so toxic that it explodes as it was in case with #metoo and #timeisup movement. obviously itâ€™s pronounced more in certain countries and industries but since we all inhabit the same planet, i think itâ€™s important to talk about it even if we are not affected directly. plus there are so many smaller scale ways in which our boundaries can be violated daily. by â€œourâ€ i mean both men and women, however the conditioning is very different when it comes to how we deal with it. men are allowed to get angry, women not so much. we are expected to be â€œniceâ€ at all times - even when the situation calls for not a nice response. this double standard is a bit like - women are allowed to be vulnerable and cry, men not. both of those scenarios produce the same result - suppressed emotions. which can lead to possible health problems later on. this is not a call to get angry every time someone is rude to you but rather to learn to confront/stand up for yourself in a healthy way when itâ€™s needed. something i avoided at all costs in the past as it felt much safer to just withdraw and ignore/avoid the person. there is however no growth in this approach and 2018 was big on boundary setting  lessons. #boundaries #selfawareness #growth #yinyang #takeyourpowerback #empowerment #comfortzone #resolutions #photooftheday #instalike #instagood #foodforthought ğŸŒšğŸŒ

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
new blog post: why all women should eat alone.

many of you have probably seen the @bbcnews article floating around this week about a restaurant in new york (@nello is the name if you're curious), that told a woman she couldn't sit at the bar alone as the owner was wanting to, and i quote, "crackdown on hookers." how considerate *eye roll*

but it brought attention to the much bigger picture of the stigmas placed around a woman who, by choice, wants to do something alone.

whether that be traveling, eating, or simply existing -- why does society still feel like women are these feeble and incapable creatures, waiting on a man to save us?

the male savior complex in the hetero world is sickening, and it feeds into the narrative that women who navigate this world alone, are incomplete.

as i spoke on the phone with the bbc reporter, i shared a handful of stories from the past three years of times i was singled out in a restaurant or public setting, with the assumption that i was soliciting my services to men or waiting on a customer for the night.

because it's not so much the idea that a woman can be beautiful, intelligent, and confident in her skin, it's the stigma we place around that -- assuming sheâ€™s in constant pursuit of a man to help fund it.

women, please read my plea at the link in my bio (bit.ly/diningsolo), and i hope we can all collectively, no matter where we live, normalize the fact that we, too, can exist confidently and independently -- by choice.

photo credit | @thecatchmeifyoucan
name: Gloria Atanmo, The Blog Abroad

text:
mantan gubernur dki jakarta basuki tjahaja purnama masuk daftar bergengsi â€œtop global thinkers 2017â€ versi majalah ternama foreign policy. pria yang kerap disapa ahok itu bergabung dengan tokoh-tokoh dunia ternama. mereka antara lain presiden perancis emmanuel macron, presiden korea selatan moon jae-in, pemimpin oposisi inggris jeremy corbyn, senator california sekaligus capres potensial as di 2020 kamala harris, the silence breakers, para perempuan penggerak gerakan fenomenal #metoo, serta nama ternama lainnya di daftar yang dirilis awal pekan ini. tercatat, ada 48 tokoh yang dinilai sebagai sosok yang mendefinisikan tahun 2017 dengan kontribusi menonjol yang membentuk pemikiran dunia.

artikel ini telah tayang di kompas.com dengan judul "ahok masuk jajaran "para pemikir dunia" ", https://internasional.kompas.com/read/2017/12/07/05100021/ahok-masuk-jajaran-para-pemikir-dunia?utm_source=twitter&utm_medium=refferal&utm_campaign=sticky_mobile.

check out the psa we put together. link to podcast is in bio.

text:
i just wanted to share my new favorite necklace. i love the style and feel of this. i can adjust my chain to 3 different lengths which i find so useful for different outfits. 
the pendant is from @awarecauses where they make them for different causes. mine stand for ptsd and sexual assualt. 
because of my experiences with both, i proudly wear it about to bring awareness to these. they tend to go hand in hand, as forced sexual contact can flip you into fight, flight and freeze. leaving you constantly on alert for the next 'attack'. these are experienced differently depending on the person and the healing time line changes for everyone. when the events keep happening or other pile on top, ptsd can become cptsd. its hard to see when these things have occured to a person. you do not see a broken arm, usually more of a broken spirit. 
be gentle with those around you and yourself â™¡â™¡ to go with this
i have a series of poetry on my other account @mahriyahwillow for the #metoo movement.
#wordsfortheworldmetoo .
.
.
thanks for reading!
go check them out and show support. there are many different options!
.
.
.

text:
january: #humantrafficking awareness month
â€¢
wisdom wednesday
â€¢
here is a question that some may not think about: â€œwhat if a trafficked person consents?â€
â€¢
with the #metoo movement shedding light on just how little many people know about consent, we knew this was a chance to discuss this seemingly fuzzy concept.
â€¢
consent: permission for something to happen or agreement to do something.
â€¢
but the consent of the trafficked person becomes irrelevant whenever any of the 'means' of trafficking are used. a child cannot consent even if the 'means' are not involved.
â€¢
what are the â€˜meansâ€™ of trafficking?
â€¢
force (ex: beating, burning, sexual assault, rape, confinement, physical restraint)
â€¢
fraud (ex: false promises, deceitful enticing and affectionate behavior, lying about working conditions)
â€¢
coercion (ex: threats of serious harm or restraint, intimidation and humiliation, enforcement of trivial demands, intense manipulation, isolation, creating dependency and fear of independence)
â€¢
ultimately, consent â€œdoesnâ€™t countâ€ if any of these examples were used to convince the victim to reluctantly agree to the terms presented to them.
â€¢
so if a person is being trafficked, they are victim to someone(s) that are using tactics to force them into usually illegal actions for profit.
â€¢
bottom line: a trafficked person does not consent to the illegal activities they â€œagreeâ€ to participate in. the force, fraud and/or coercion cancels out the â€œconsentâ€.
â€¢
we hope this has shed some light on the internal struggle a victim of human trafficking experiences and that you are encouraged to help end human trafficking.

text:
Â« p o e m Â»
.
.
.
too depressing 
to listen to the words 
who are the only one 
that can relate 
to my scattered feeling 
it's all too familiar to me
the silent tears 
hushed away by beats 
the words filling up each empty hole
pretending i'm not alone 
that i have someone 
whispering lullabies 
to put me in to a dreamless sleep
.
.
.
// ayesha fatimah .
.

text:
i wrote this piece for all those women, who feel trapped and vulnerable in their marriage or relationship. they feel they need to hold on because of the liabilities and pressures society places upon them, despite knowing their relationship is over. i have seen many women who are fully aware of their partners infidelity, but are afraid to let them go. they have consciously accepted to carry on with the relationship, feeling afraid, insecure and helpless. these taboos we take so seriously on ourselves have never served anyone for their betterment, so why do we let it dig deeper into our wounds, causing us even more pain. and i ask what are you afraid of? 
afraid to let go, because you donâ€™t have faith in yourself? 
afraid to let go, because your insecurities get in the way of seeing a future without them?
afraid to let go, because you have children? 
afraid to let go, because you will be labelled a divorcee? 
afraid to let go, because you are concerned about what people will think? 
afraid to let go, because you have no choice? 
and thatâ€™s where we are wrong, because we do have a choice. our choices shape the life we live and if wrong choices are made, we stop ourselves from becoming someone we could have been. we should not look for our answers in others, when we can find them within ourselves. itâ€™s okay if our answers donâ€™t match the societal norms or stereotype. in this â€˜willâ€™ to fit with the society standards, we have destroyed our concept of ethics within us. we doubt ourselves so much, that we have become our own enemies. donâ€™t be afraid to let go for the right reasons. nothing will happen to us unless we allow it to happen. by letting go, we are able to see the real damage and pain we were inflicting on ourselves and in our lives. we are not as helpless as we think we are, we are individuals that have an innate ability to survive on our own. so itâ€™s apparent that we need to in our lives learn to fight our own battles alone, with the mind and heart our creator has given us to use. donâ€™t become a slave to your circumstances or other people. the day you decide to change, is the day when the universe conspires to get you through it. - uzma khan
name: Uzma Khan

text:
rachel louise carson (may 27, 1907 â€“ april 14, 1964) was an american marine biologist, author, and conservationist whose book silent spring and other writings are credited with advancing the global environmental movement.
carson began her career as an aquatic biologist in the u.s. bureau of fisheries, and became a full-time nature writer in the 1950s.
her widely praised 1951 bestseller the sea around us won her a u.s. national book award, recognition as a gifted writer, and financial security.
her next book, the edge of the sea, and the reissued version of her first book, under the sea wind, were also bestsellers.
this sea trilogy explores the whole of ocean life from the shores to the depths.
late in the 1950s, carson turned her attention to conservation, especially some problems that she believed were caused by synthetic pesticides.
the result was the book silent spring (1962), which brought environmental concerns to an unprecedented share of the american people.
although silent spring was met with fierce opposition by chemical companies, it spurred a reversal in national pesticide policy, which led to a nationwide ban on ddt and other pesticides.
it also inspired a grassroots environmental movement that led to the creation of the u.s. environmental protection agency.
carson was posthumously awarded the presidential medal of freedom by jimmy carter.

text:
speak out sisterhood is growing daily.

our group for survivors of domestic abuse and sexual abuse is focused on enabling survivors to not feel alone and isolated.

there's daily tips, health care advice, resilience coaching and sign posting. 
you can watch or interact.
either way it's cool.

what we all know is that we are stronger than we knew.

if you know anyone who might want to hop over here's the link.

text: i cant believe iâ€™m posting this but honestly i think it would make me feel better because right now i feel like it's this horrible thing i should keep secret. i didn't ask for any of this and maybe this post helps someone else. this is a huge problem that needs to be addressed and dealt with. sexual assault something that no one likes to hear or talk about. my first semester of college i was sexually assaulted and alcohol did play an important role. i thought i was safe where i was but being my first semester i was desperate for friends. itâ€™s obvious i didnâ€™t pick very good ones. the reason iâ€™m sharing my story is not for pitty but to show people this is a real thing. there are so many girls i still know in high school getting ready to graduate and go to college. i would like you all to read this carefully so maybe you can avoid a horrible situation like i was in. if your going to drink just make sure you have really close friends with you. also please know your limits because if you canâ€™t fight back youâ€™re such an easy target. also be careful who you trust because there are bad people in this world. after it happened i didnâ€™t go to class and my grades dropped. i spent a lot of my time heavily drinking to try and suppress the pain. this is not a way to cope and it only made my life spiral out of control even more. if this has happened to you go seek professional help. donâ€™t try to bury it because it will make its way back to the surface. i still have nightmares and i still cry over it but iâ€™m actually dealing with it now instead of burying it. so girls please be careful bc it can and will ruin your life. now i have something to say to you fellas. women are not toys. we are not objects. if you donâ€™t get a definite yes then donâ€™t force it. if a girl is passed out drunk that doesnâ€™t mean yes. if a girl is dressed provocatively that doesnâ€™t mean yes. sit back and think with me for a second and ask yourself would you like your daughter to be treated the way you treat women? if not then change! be a gentleman! if you have a son right now then please teach him how you should respect women. this experience has changed me and my life forever. #metoo

text:
sc imposes blanket ban on yellow goggles

the sc on monday imposed a nationwide blanket ban on the manufacture and sale of yellow goggles. in its verdict, the court said only shades of black, brown and blue glasses shall be allowed to be sold in the country from now on.

the apex court announced the verdict after citing examples of people losing their sanity after wearing yellow shades. the 800 page judgement mentions celebrities like hardik pandya, whose case is subjudice for speaking nonsense on the koffee with karan show. another case was that of rani mukherjee for her statement at a chat show that women are responsible for #metoo. and lastly sonakshi sinha for her father shatrughan sinha.

text:
#wow on michele beck
i had the privilege of being shot by the director michele beck for this amazing documentary of what pole dancing meant to me and so many women. she needs help !
please contact amazon and demand that my erotic body be made available again! videodirect-support@amazon.com
even though my erotic body still has large numbers of people watching it on amazon in the us, germany and the uk and has received tons of positive reviews, amazon has unexpectedly decided to make it unavailable!! they did not give me a clear explanation why and have not responded to any of my inquiries. after doing some research i found out that amazon has cut a large portion of their indie films this week. they dropped movies with subject matter that they felt was inappropriate to the new image they are trying to create for their online streaming. itâ€™s sad that an honest, intimate and personal look at womenâ€™s sensuality and empowerment is a problematic topic for them. it is hard to imagine that as this time, during the #metoo movement, that they would choose to silence womenâ€™s voices. my erotic body has had such a powerful impact on people. it has given women freedom in their bodies, helped men understand women a bit better, helped cancer survivors reconnect to their sensuality, helped people think about the importance of community- and on and on and on. there are so many important things to be gained from this film and it needs to stay on amazon and be available to a wide audience.

a civil suit against donald trump alleging he raped a 13-year-old girl was dismissed in california in may 2016, refiled in new york in june 2016, and dropped again in november 2016.

a federal lawsuit filed in new york accuses republican presidential candidate donald trump of repeatedly raping a 13-year-old girl more than 20 years ago, at several upper east side parties hosted by convicted sex offender and notorious billionaire investor jeffrey epstein.
the suit, first reported by the real deal, accuses trump and epstein of luring the anonymous plaintiff and other young women to four parties at epsteinâ€™s so-called wexner mansion at 9 east 71st street. epstein allegedly lured the plaintiff, identified in the suit only as jane doe, with promises of a modeling career and cash.
another anonymous woman, identified in additional testimony as tiffany doe, corroborates janeâ€™s allegations, testifying that she met epstein at port authority, where he hired her to recruit other young girls for his parties. trump had known epstein for seven years in 1994 when he attended the parties at wexner, according to the suit. he also allegedly knew that the plaintiff was 13 years old.
jane doe filed a similar suit in california in april, under the name katie johnson, also accusing trump and epstein of rape. that suit was dismissed on the grounds of improper paperwork â€” the address affiliated with her name was found to be abandoned. todayâ€™s suit confirms that the plaintiffs are one and the same.

20% of teens are clinically depressed. the real tragedy lies with how their parents and teachers approach the subject. so many dismiss the symptoms of depression as mere adolescent adjustments, a disconcerting number of these teens go without the treatment they need to enjoy a healthy, happy life. to anyone who needs to talk, remember that you are not alone. if you are in need of someone to talk to. please contact our peacemakers office: (786) 888-4751. 
don't be afraid to reach out to a helpline 1-800-662-help.

lawsuit charges donald trump with raping a 13-year-old girl

a civil suit against donald trump alleging he raped a 13-year-old girl was dismissed in california in may 2016, refiled in new york in june 2016, and dropped again in november 2016.

a federal lawsuit filed in new york accuses republican presidential candidate donald trump of repeatedly raping a 13-year-old girl more than 20 years ago, at several upper east side parties hosted by convicted sex offender and notorious billionaire investor jeffrey epstein.
the suit, first reported by the real deal, accuses trump and epstein of luring the anonymous plaintiff and other young women to four parties at epsteinâ€™s so-called wexner mansion at 9 east 71st street. epstein allegedly lured the plaintiff, identified in the suit only as jane doe, with promises of a modeling career and cash.
another anonymous woman, identified in additional testimony as tiffany doe, corroborates janeâ€™s allegations, testifying that she met epstein at port authority, where he hired her to recruit other young girls for his parties. trump had known epstein for seven years in 1994 when he attended the parties at wexner, according to the suit. he also allegedly knew that the plaintiff was 13 years old.
jane doe filed a similar suit in california in april, under the name katie johnson, also accusing trump and epstein of rape. that suit was dismissed on the grounds of improper paperwork â€” the address affiliated with her name was found to be abandoned. todayâ€™s suit confirms that the plaintiffs are one and the same.

text:
ok. 
as many of you know, i havenâ€™t always had kind words to say about chris brown. his history of abuse of both rihanna and karreuche rubbed me the wrong way entirely. however, i do believe people can change if they want to. it seems that maybe chris has been trying to change, but hasnâ€™t had the support he needs. 
fast forward to this week, heâ€™s now being accused of rape. i have to say, i was a little taken aback. iâ€™ve also be slow to speak on the issue because the truth is, rape allegations can be tricky. 
i am always on the side of the victim. let me make that clear. from r kelly, to harvey weinstein, to bill cosby, to woody allen, the victims are my only concern-ever. we need to create a culture that counters the rape culture that is so prevalent in this society. a culture that doesnâ€™t shame, intimidate or blame women for the actions of their assailants. 
however, in this case, it seems weâ€™ll soon find that the allegations against chris are false. reports are saying that chris plans to sue. and since i often speak out about rape, sexual harassment and the like, i have to be fair and say that i hope he does sue and i hope he wins, if he in fact is innocent. 
while false rape allegations are at about 2-8% of all allegations, we know that sometimes, these kinds of things happen. and i want to be clear that i think thatâ€™s disgusting. personally, i feel it should be common practice to sue someone and sentence them to jail time for making false allegations. period.

tonight, the penny stamps speaker series presents juyeon kim. born in seoul, south korea, juyeon kim works and lives in new york. she has shown in both solo and group exhibitions nationally and internationally including new york, washington, dc, shanghai, and seoul. 
a 2018â€“2019 roman witt resident, kim is creating a multimedia installation work in collaboration with the stamps school community and composer george tsontakis that seeks to explore themes around korean â€œcomfort womenâ€â€” the female prisoners of the japanese army during world war ii.  kim states: â€œalthough my installation project was conceived and initiated before my awareness of the #metoo movement developing in the states and around the world, it seems to me to be so poignantly connected to the historical plight of women everywhere. while the travails of the korean â€˜comfort womenâ€™ are an extreme example of womenâ€™s integrity being compromised, the assault sadly continues on various levels and by different degrees.â€

text:
we canâ€™t change what we do not first acknowledge ğŸ™ğŸ½ this is so important for us to keep in mind, both in the context of the world outside of us and the world within us...
â€”
when it comes to the external world, we must acknowledge its shortcomings and raise awareness of its problems in order to make changes. thatâ€™s why itâ€™s so important to talk about issues like mental health, toxic masculinity, the #metoo movement and any other cause that raises awareness about an issue...
â€”
by acknowledging the existence of the problem, we create the space to discuss solutions to it, following which we can take action to resolve the problem.
â€”
but this also applies to whatâ€™s within us! we cannot change what we do not first acknowledge. if we donâ€™t accept that something isnâ€™t right with us, we canâ€™t change it. if we mask the problem with distractions and denial, if we try to bury or bottle it up, if we resist or fight what is true and real, we donâ€™t stand a chance of changing it...
â€”
we can only change what we acknowledge. we can only change what we understand. we can only change what we accept, without judgement.
â€”
yes, itâ€™s painful to admit that thereâ€™s a problem. yes, our pride and ego feel humiliated and ashamed. yes, they may even feel worthless and weak...
â€”
but we must recognise that it takes strength to confront an issue and accept its existence without judgement or resistance. only when we acknowledge and accept the situation can we begin to transform it.
â€”
so, whatever youâ€™re experiencing in your internal and external worlds, begin by honestly acknowledging and accepting it as your current reality. take responsibility and ownership over the issue. let go of what you canâ€™t control, and focus on what you can control. and then take action to change your situation for the better! ğŸ™ğŸ½ğŸ’ªğŸ½

text:
personal and social education lessons to get #metoo makeover
#
image copyright getty images image caption teaching about relationships, consent sexual harrassment and sexuality will be updated for the #metoo generation the way schools teach pupils about relationships and consent in scotland is to be overhauled in the wake of the #metoo movement.personal and social education (pse) teachers will be given new support and resources to help them inform youngsters about issues such as sexual harassment and online influences.the move was announced by education secretary john swinney.a recent review of pse found teaching "inconsistent and inadequate".pupils will also become involved in choosing what they learn, with the reform "enabling pupils to design and deliver learning that is relevant to them".in 2017, msps on holyrood's education committee uncovered evidence that for some young people, particularly those who identify as lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender or intersex (lgbti), "sex education comes from the internet, including pornography, due to a lack of adequate provision within school".it also found the issue of sexual consent was not covered consistently in classes.'preparation for learning, work and life'a total of 16 recommendations for change were made as a result of the review carried out after that, with mr swinney saying these had all been accepted by the scottishâ€¦

text:
challenge is inevitable. yet we rise... i saw this image a few days ago that reminded me diamonds are formed under pressure, wine can only be made with crushed grapes, and seeds grow in the damp dirt. 
we too, are shaped and polished by the challenges we encounter. .
why shouldn't we own what has shaped us and take on that mountain in style... when life gets challenging, embrace the obstacle. .

text:
it used to be that women were expected to, felt obligated to, put their dreams on hold while they took care of their significant other, their children, and their significant otherâ€™s career.  weâ€™ve made a lot of strides with this, but still have work to do!  it is ok for us to feel fulfilled! it is ok for us to work on making our dreams a reality instead of just keeping them as dreams.  how cool is it for our children and significant other to see us happy, fulfilled, and living our purpose.  what great modeling it is for us to demonstrate to others.  if we are feeling fulfilled in our lives - our children, significant other, family and friends are getting a much happier, healthier, and content version of us.  sounds like a win-win to me!

henson didnâ€™t take into consideration that you could mute musicians on spotify, not directors. 
taraji p. henson attempted to have a â€œwokeâ€ moment on social media which undoubtedly backfired in her face. the actress faced backlash after she tried to compare the publicâ€™s treatment of r. kelly and harvey weinstein, but was quickly reminded that the point went over her head completely.

taraji p. henson shared several since-deleted posts on her instagram story comparing the #muterkelly hashtag to the #muteharveyweinstein hashtag. many quickly reminded henson that r. kelly is a musician, thus making it feasible to mute him while weinstein is a film executive who sits behind the scenes. however, many also revealed that weinstein is actually facing charges for his alleged sex crimes while kellz only has a hashtag so far.

henson took to twitter shortly after facing backlash for her post. â€œlet me be clear r. kelly is guilty and wrong and should be muted period!!!!,â€ she wrote.

henson undoubtedly received an overwhelming amount of backlash for the post, but there were a few others who were a bit more empathetic to the point she was trying to make. one person pointed out that henson is an actress in the film industry and the impact of weinsteinâ€™s actions have more of an impact on her than r. kelly. 
hensonâ€™s comments faced similar backlash to those of erykah badu who appeared to have defended kellz at a concert. badu later took to twitter to clarify her tweets, which also faced public scrutiny. â€œi love you. unconditionally. that doesnâ€™t mean i support your poor choices. i want healing for you and anyone you have hurt as a result of you being hurt,â€ she wrote. peep the some of the responses in the full story at www.itskenbarbie.com or swipe. what do you guys think? #taraji #tarajiphenson #tarajihenson #rkelly #muterkelly #robertkelly #trappedinthecloset #survivingrkelly #metoo #harveyweinstein #entertainment #entertainmentnews #entertainmentblog #empire #gossip #empireonfox

june bloom, a young assistant writer on a late night talk show called stay up with hugo best is working hard to satisfy her own aspirations and those of her demanding parents. one night she bumps into the star of the show, hugo best, outside of a small club. after a small discussion she is invited to stay with him at his private home in connecticut for the memorial day weekend. june doesnâ€™t know exactly why she is invited and while she has a had distant attraction to the star for a while, she doesnâ€™t know how this would translate to real life. what does it mean to be invited for a weekend away? what expectations are held and by whom?

in the era of the #metoo movement, one in which women are slowly beginning to feel more empowered emotionally, physically and sexually, men had better know that things that once worked for them will no longer. 
by now you are probably thinking you know the storyline this book will follow but you might not. the only way to find out? is to read it. i hope you enjoy this fresh and cleverly written novel as much as i did.

text:
artist. writer. wanderer. miscellaneous prop hoarder. food taster. flower plucker. feminist. fighter. healer. nourisher. sister. daughter. latina. lover.
in light of a new lifestyle and a drastic shift in perspective, i felt the need to share my part, in the #iammany campaign.
iâ€™m a believer in putting my health and wellness first, and i believe it starts from within. mentally and emotionally, our well being starts from our hearts and our minds.
it begins with the fiercest self love, and the need to be authentic and true.
the #iammany campaign promotes the belief that women are meant to be dynamic and multidimensional. this, i believe, is the root of who we are, as women. the root of our self discovery, our mentality, our well being, our push for change, our impact on each other, and our impact on ourselves.
and iâ€™m here to say, iâ€™ve hesitated with this for too long. iâ€™ve pushed and pulled and collided with myself, to find my one piece, my one thing, my one label. but, i was not meant to be one. i was meant to be many. i choose to be many.
you, we, women, are many.
-

i thought that was really powerful. but iâ€™m also saddened knowing that so many abusers have multiple victims in their lifetime.

iâ€™m sure some have too many to count. i know my abusive ex has numerous women across the country who have stories of his abuse.

how many of us have to band together before these abusers see justice? i know so many of us have poured our hearts and our truths out in court rooms, police stations, and hospitals just to see nothing come of it.

i know even more of us have stayed silent because weâ€™ve seen firsthand how survivors can be treated. we know that even if multiple victims come forward, there will still be those who echo chants about how we are looking for attention or how we must be lying since we kept our secret for so long.

i donâ€™t know an answer on how we fix abusers. some argue that once theyâ€™re a certain age, itâ€™s too late for them to recognize the errors of their ways. but i want you to know, that there are people out there fighting for usâ€”making sure that there arenâ€™t more victims, making sure that your story is heard.
sending love and strength to all of you today. some days are hard, and thatâ€™s okay. itâ€™s just a part of our healing journey. #weareher

during this time i set up @surviveandthriveau as an expression of my thoughts and somewhere to post the blogs i had written that would hopefully be read by women that have experienced any sort of sexual violence. 
when i qualified as a coach, i realised that these blogs and the instagram page where keeping me stuck in my experiences rather than my experiences being a smaller piece of a much larger self identity... so i stopped writing for a while to work that out in my mind.... i feel i have now done that.... so today i am merging them both and â€˜coming out!â€™ i no longer feel the need to hide my passion in supporting women to find their happiness after trauma and i no longer feel i need to hide parts of me to the world ğŸ’•

text:
has anyone ever seen (or read the book) "the secret"? everytime i watch it it blows my mind..
.
i don't think i've ever seen single documentary that literally shifts my mood and makes me feel like a bad-ass mofo by the end of it..
.
it reminds me the power that we all have in our mind.  it makes it mega simple to use to.
.
highly recommend giving it watch if you haven't yet but i'll break it down reaaaaal quick..
.
step 1. ask - most people have no idea what the fuck they want.  they know what they don't want though.  think about the universe being a catalog and you can have anything you want.  that's step one, figure out what you want to become, receive, or create. .
step 2 believe - (black preacher voice) you just gotta believe that it's on the way son!  although you don't have it yet you need to have an unwavering belief in the future of whatever it is you asked for and know that it's on the way.
.
step 3 receive - this is the part that trips everyone (#metoo) up...
.
"those that believe they have, shall receive" - jesus
.
going into your mind is the most powerful way from my experience to do this part.  you need to "make believe" and feel as though the reality you want already is.  so you're receiving in your body and mind.  see it, feel it, smell it.  act as if it already is done.  ie. you should be bubbling with an amazing feeling if you've done this right.
.
and once the emotion is place with your thought intention (step 1)...
.
higher power, universe, god, or whatever you want to call it kicks in.  it works in mysterious ways but from my understanding the universe responds to frequency and vibration (thoughts and emotions...good & bad 'vibes)
.
just go watch the doc.  it's phenomenal haha :)
.
enjoy your day nerds!
.
.
.
.
.

step 1. ask - most people have no idea what the fuck they want.  they know what they do not want though.  think about the universe being a catalog and you can have anything you want.  that's step one, figure out what you want to become, receive, or create. .
step 2 believe - (black preacher voice) you just gotta believe that it is on the way son!  although you do not have it yet you need to have an unwavering belief in the future of whatever it is you asked for and know that it is on the way.
.
step 3 receive - this is the part that trips everyone (#metoo) up...
.
"those that believe they have, shall receive" - jesus
.
going into your mind is the most powerful way from my experience to do this part.  you need to "make believe" and feel as though the reality you want already is.  so you are receiving in your body and mind.  see it, feel it, smell it.  act as if it already is done.  ie. you should be bubbling with an amazing feeling if you have done this right.
.
and once the emotion is place with your thought intention (step 1)...
.
higher power, universe, god, or whatever you want to call it kicks in.  it works in mysterious ways but from my understanding the universe responds to frequency and vibration (thoughts and emotions...good & bad 'vibes)
.
just go watch the doc.  it is phenomenal haha :)
.
enjoy your day nerds!

text:
books that changed my life ğŸ“š
.
i was able to start reading again in 2018. this was huge after not being able to read for years due to symptoms from chronic illness. i thought i might never be able to read again, so now i havenâ€™t been able to stop
.
pictured are some of the top books that helped transform my life in the last 6 months. i grew so much in the second half of 2018. i began to learn more about myself, how my mind and body work, what i want, and how to get it. i have to be honest, the entire womenâ€™s movement and #metoo movement have had a huge impact on me, as well (we can save that for another day)
.
iâ€™ve really struggled, mentally, with chronic illness for many years. itâ€™s been terrifying and hard. i didnâ€™t know how to get out of the spiral of negative thoughts i was in. i kept reading about the power of the mind, neuroplasticity, and changing your thoughts, but for some reason non of it clicked and i was still deep in the hole
.
the above books helped in reframing my thinking, flipped a switch for me, and allowed me to understand my own power and control in my life and healing process
.

text:
one day my brain will tell 
what happened
with that 3 days fell
my life
into what i thought maybe hell 
lâ™¡r

i've been reading a lot and what i know for certain is this

bipolar 1 is what's considered the most severe on the spectrum of bipolar.

yes i had 2 psychotic episodes in which i dissociated completely from reality

no i'm not making that up

i sure wish i could tell you it was drugs

but it was not

i am so much more than my brain chemistry

but that doesnt mean that i cant take ownership and apologize for the things i said and take responsibility that others have feelings that can be bruised too even if they werent. 
if you are not sleeping, having amazing multi tasking moments but can barely remember who the president is. if you have boughts of endless sadness but still feel like smiling...talk to someone who is your ride or die anyone. i didnt realize just how triggered i was getting because of other peoples suffering around me because i was raised to never "play the victim" . but i would never say that to a someone with a physical illness....why would i say that to myself now. 
#bipolar #mentalhealthawareness #metoo #mentalhealth #bekind #bepositive #positivevibes #happynewyear #happynewyear #2019

text:
my strength comes in many forms, some times i am standing tall and proud, my shoulders back, my head held high and ready to face the world.  other times, i feel vulnerable, raw, worn, and run down...my heart and soul both hurt and all i can manage to do is wake up small and mournful.  these days i need help, these days i need support...someone to remind me this is only temporary and soon i will be standing tall and strong in my power once more.
.

text:
this saturday!! consent seems to be on everyoneâ€™s tongue with the #metoo movement and the continuous discourse in the public sphere. it is most often a conversation about sexual harassment and violence or within the context of romantic relationships and sexual encounters. leaving the discussion in the realm of sexual experiences (whether negative or positive) leaves out the importance of consent in our own bodies, families, and workplacesâ€¦ and the systems that created and reinforce perpetual consent violations. 
join touk keo (founder of the @radmeditationforbipoc and healer) and jess devries (sex and intimacy coach) to take a closer look at general consent including: - what is rape culture? - what conditions reinforce rape culture in individuals and american society as a whole? - when/how did we lose our personal agency? - how can we feel consent in our bodies? - how does being in trauma response affect our ability to give informed consent? - how does consent look different for the bipoc community and for the white community? 
this workshop will provide a framework for the cultural systems that we live in and how to connect with the knowledge of our bodies to help strengthen our personal agency. 
general information: 
date: saturday, january 26th
time: 2:00pm - 4:30pm
location: speec space - 5010 n commercial ave. portland, or 97211
accessibility: the speec space has two steps to enter and the bathroom is not currently ada accessible. it is close to trimet lines 44 and 72.
cost: $10-$30 sliding scale

space is limited. to reserve your spot please use the following link: paypal.me/jessdevries1 -  please add your first and last name and the class name to the note when you send it in. or click the link to register in my bio. 
please dm with any questions regarding this workshop.

text:
hey friends! @touk_keo and i are going to be teaching some important shit this weekend. if you are free on saturday from 2-4:30, weâ€™d love to have you join us!  details below. .
.
this saturday!! consent seems to be on everyoneâ€™s tongue with the #metoo movement and the continuous discourse in the public sphere. it is most often a conversation about sexual harassment and violence or within the context of romantic relationships and sexual encounters. leaving the discussion in the realm of sexual experiences (whether negative or positive) leaves out the importance of consent in our own bodies, families, and workplacesâ€¦ and the systems that created and reinforce perpetual consent violations. .
.
join touk keo (founder of the @radmeditationforbipoc and healer) and jess devries (sex and intimacy coach) to take a closer look at general consent including: - what is rape culture? - what conditions reinforce rape culture in individuals and american society as a whole? - when/how did we lose our personal agency? - how can we feel consent in our bodies? - how does being in trauma response affect our ability to give informed consent? - how does consent look different for the bipoc community and for the white community? 
this workshop will provide a framework for the cultural systems that we live in and how to connect with the knowledge of our bodies to help strengthen our personal agency. 
general information: 
date: saturday, january 26th
time: 2:00pm - 4:30pm
location: speec space - 5010 n commercial ave. portland, or 97211
accessibility: the speec space has two steps to enter and the bathroom is not currently ada accessible. it is close to trimet lines 44 and 72.
cost: $10-$30 sliding scale
.
.
space is limited. to reserve your spot please use the following link: paypal.me/jessdevries1 -  please add your first and last name and the class name to the note when you send it in. or click the link to register in my bio. .
.
please dm with any questions regarding this workshop.

text:
love her wild. if you don't know what we mean, check @sydneyunfiltered's post from today, it's a little nod to the wild women out there.

this week, we made our way up toward ventura this week so we could relax and go see @kylesmithjams on thursday night. as we were exploring the beaches, we found this mural, and had a little photoshoot.

on friday, we are scooting down to the santa monica @rei for sydney's final talk of this leg of the #hikingmyfeelingstour that night at 7pm. if you want to learn more about what #hikingmyfeelings is, if you want to hike the #transcatalinatrail someday, if you #believesurvivors or just need to hear #metoo, if you have #type2diabetes or know someone who does, if you're tired of carrying your #traumapack, or if you just want to understand what we mean when we say #homeiswhereyouparkit, come on down. it's a party on santa monica boulevard!
